  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Shelter solutions for vulnerable communities in North East Syria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to provide durable shelter solutions for extremely vulnerable returnees and host communities in Deir-ez-Zor city. 

The shelter needs in Syria remain significant seven years into the conflict. The local infrastructure, especially in areas such as Deir-ez-Zor which have faced sustained offensives, is severely damaged and inhabitable posing protection risks and impeding recovery. With constrained livelihoods options, and competing basic needs priorities, the local population has little resources to access dignified shelters and therefore resort to crowded and unsafe dwellings. 

Medair strategy is in line with the second shelter objective of the 2018 HRP- by building resilience of the extremely vulnerable population of Deir-ez-Zor city by rehabilitating damage housing structures. The implementation location is in line with the Syria Humanitarian Fund-First Standard Allocation Strategy focusing on areas with severe needs- Deir-ez-Zor city is considered a severity scale 4 area.

The specific activities, both in terms of input and process are in line with the Shelter Sector guidance. The response will be coordinated through the sector to avoid duplication and ensure those most in need are reached.  100 households will gain access to safe and dignified shelters through the rehabilitation of dwellings. Shelter adaptions will be carried out for 10 households to improve access and independence of PWPDs and the elderly. The rehabilitation will be undertaken taking into account HLP components and ensuring infrastructure work is conducted as per national standards in a safe and accountable way.</narrative>
  </description>
